      <h2>The Challenge of 50-State Scale</h2>
      <SketchContainer sketchId="data-bars" height="var(--space-4xl)" mobileHeight="var(--space-3xl)" ariaLabel="Data ingestion stream visualization" />

      <p>
        Public record data in the United States is structurally fragmented. Each state maintains its own Uniform Commercial Code (UCC) filing system, often with proprietary interfaces, inconsistent data schemas, and aggressive anti-scraping measures. I directed the architecture of a 50-state aggregation platform designed to normalize this fragmentation into a single, high-reliability B2B data pipeline.<Cite id={1} author="Trask, Stephen" title="The High Cost of Data Fragmentation" source="Journal of Digital Commerce" year={2022} />
      </p>

      <MermaidDiagram
        caption="Adversarial Extraction Pipeline: Distributed agents bypass anti-bot measures to normalize inconsistent state records into a unified DuckDB/PostgreSQL warehouse."
        chart={`graph TD
    S1[State Portal: CA] --> A1[Agent: Chrome/Puppeteer]
    S2[State Portal: NY] --> A2[Agent: Python/Playwright]
    S3[State Portal: TX] --> A3[Agent: Rust/Raw HTTP]
    
    A1 --> Q[SQS Job Queue]
    A2 --> Q
    A3 --> Q
    
    Q --> N[Normalization Engine]
    N --> DB[(PostgreSQL Master)]
    N --> Analytics[DuckDB OLAP]
    
    subgraph Infrastructure [AWS / Terraform]
      VPC[VPC] --> Lambda[Scaling Scraper Lambdas]
      Lambda --> Proxies[Rotating Residential Proxies]
    end
    
    A1 -.->|traffic| Proxies
    A2 -.->|traffic| Proxies`}
      />

      <h2>Technical Implementation</h2>
      <p>
        The system utilizes a <strong>Polymorphic Agent Architecture</strong>. Because state portals use different defensive technologies (CAPTCHA, TLS fingerprinting, rate limiting), a single scraping tool was insufficient. The pipeline dynamically selects between three agent types: heavy (Puppeteer/Chromium), medium (Playwright/Stealth), and light (Rust/Tokio) based on the target portal's security posture.<Cite id={2} author="Goyal, A." title="Adversarial Data Engineering" source="ACM Systems" year={2024} />
      </p>

      <CodeStructure lang="python" caption="Agent Selection Logic: Dynamically routing extraction jobs based on state-specific defense signatures." filename="scrapper/orchestrator/routing.py">
{`from enum import Enum
from typing import TypedDict

class DefensePosture(Enum):
    LOW = "low"
    MEDIUM = "fingerprinting"
    HIGH = "adversarial"

class Job(TypedDict):
    state: str
    priority: int

def select_agent(job: Job) -> str:
    posture = get_state_defense_signature(job['state'])
    
    match posture:
        case DefensePosture.HIGH:
            return "agents.heavy.chromium_stealth"
        case DefensePosture.MEDIUM:
            return "agents.medium.playwright_node"
        case _:
            return "agents.light.rust_tokio"

# Scaling logic handles 50 concurrent state crawls
`}
      </CodeStructure>

      <h2>Infrastructure & Reliability</h2>
      <p>
        Reliability was the primary KPI. I implemented a **Zero-Trust Extraction Protocol** where every record must pass three validation gates: schema alignment, parity checking (cross-referencing with historical snapshots), and data integrity hashing. The infrastructure is defined entirely in Terraform, enabling one-click deployment of the entire 50-state stack across AWS regions to minimize latency and bypass regional blocks.
      </p>

      <Figure alt="Validation Gate Performance" caption="System reliability metrics showing a 99.8% success rate in record normalization across adversarial portals." number={1}>
